    "comment": "Rationale: Fig.1: \"Spine changes induced by Stau1 siRNA are prevented by NMDA receptor blockade and high Mg2+\"\nFig.2: \"Impairment of FSK-induced L-LTP after Stau1 knockdown during high Mg2+ treatment\"\n\nTogether: mRNA binding/transporting protein Stau1 regulates spine morphology and late-LTP induction. The role in late-LTP induction is independent of the role in morphological changes. Literal: \"In conclusion, we found that Stau1 involvement in spine morphogenesis is dependent on NMDA receptor-mediated plasticity in hippocampal pyramidal cells. We also found that Stau1 is required for late-LTP, independently of its role in spine morphogenesis\"\n\nNote: the role as mRNA binding/transporting protein is not shown in this paper.. Experimental description: - Slice culture: The species of the cells is not stated in the paper. I have derived the species, rat, from a remark on the specificity of the shRNA sequences: \"siRNA target sequences for rat were as described\"",
